acles for fathers’ parental leave in Finland -- tCaring fathers and parental leave in prosperous times and times of crisis: the case of Iceland -- tParental leave use for different fathers: a study of the impact of three Swedish parental leave reforms -- tInternational reflections on findings -- tParental leave and fathers: extending and deepening the knowledge base -- tNordic fathers: tracking diversity and complexity -- tConclusions -- tConclusions: ‘What is constructed can be transformed’ -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe five Nordic countries, Denmark, Finland, Iceland, Norway and Sweden, are well-known for their extensive welfare system and gender equality which provides both parents with opportunities to earn and care for their children. In this topical book, expert scholars from the Nordic countries, as well as UK and the US, demonstrate how modern fatherhood is supported in the Nordic setting through family and social policies, and how these contribute to shaping and influencing the images, roles and practices of fathers in a diversity of family settings and variations of fatherhoods. This comprehensive volume will have wide international appeal for those who look to Nordic countries and their success in creating gender equal societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aFatherhoodxSocial aspectszScandinavia. 0aFathersxServices forzScandinavia. 7aFAMILY & RELATIONSHIPS / Parenting / Fatherhood.2bisacsh1 aAndersen, Arnfinn J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloksgaard, Lotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandth, Berit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuvander, Ann-Zofie, econtributor.4ctb4https://